Class SlidableList

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractList<E>
        • java.util.Vector<Slidable>
          • edu.iastate.ansci.flip.SlidableList
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Iterable<Slidable>, java.util.Collection<Slidable>, java.util.List<Slidable>, java.util.RandomAccess

    public class SlidableList
extends java.util.Vector<Slidable>
implements java.io.Serializable
    Implements two lists simultaneously. One is a simple Vector which maintains the order in which elements are added. The other is a SortList which arranges the elements in increasing order.

      • iterator

        public java.util.Iterator<Slidable> iterator()
        Creates and returns an iterator pointing to the #SortList contained by this List.

        Thus calls to the iterators next() method return Slidables that are arranged in increasing order.

        It should be noted that if any of the Slidables is moved after the iterator is created, the sorted nature of the next() calls may be lost

        Specified by:

        public double getRelativeValue(int i)

        Note that in this case index refers to the index of the sorted List

        Parameters:
        index - - the index of the desired element
        Returns:
        double - the requested distance or 0 if the index is out of bounds or if the indexed element is the minimum
